review:
I LOVE this game, really! (As you can see by my total hours of gameplay). To the point that it is painful for me to make a bad review of it, but on the following lines I'll explain my point of view.

Let's start with the good things:
[list]
[*] superb graphics & animations;
[*] funny & deep gameplay;
[*] good tutorial (although not exhaustive of the mechanics of the game) & useful combo challenges for every character; 
[*] excellent roster (only including also the DLC extra Characters).
[/list]

So, why a bad review? Cause of the following elements:
[list]
[*] [i] mediocre server stability [/i]: QUITE OFTEN, the multiplayer suffers LAG or the Internet connection to the servers falls;
[*] [i] technical issues [/i]: [strike] the UE4 (the game graphic engine) produces random crashes, & (quite often) a DRAMATIC DROP OF FRAMERATE. This happens both in single player & (a lot more) in Ranked Matches [/strike] (FIXED);
[*] [i] the online community: you won't find a fair play [/i], cause most of the people playing this title are combo machines that destroy you with 2 or 3 comboes. In the end, who wins online is the person with the best Controller or Joystic, & not the smarter (as it should be, for me). Actually, I have reached a medium-high level in Ranked matches (I am a "Demon") &, although I won 50% of matches in the past (without LAG and FRAMERATE DROPS it would have been at least 60%), at this point I am losing 90% of them cause of the frustrating, foolish, air comboes of my opponents. The basic concept that I don't like is that 90% of the results of a match are determined by those (impossible to stop, when started) air comboes. To make the combat system more fair, in my opinion Arc System should allow only 1 "cancel jump" per combo. 
[/list]

EDIT: 29/06/2020: as it is now that the technical issues have been fixed, my advice is to buy for sure this title if you are interested only in single player contents (but considering that they aren't  so many) & to think twice if you want to fight in multiplayer matches. If only was possible on Steam, I would rank this title with a "medium" evaluation. But still, I can't fully promote it.

Amazing and accessible 2D fighter. 

- Excellent roster. Not overwhelmingly large, but with enough variety between different characters that you won't really miss anyone;
- Simple to learn, complex to master mechanics; 
- Astonishing animations and art style, true to the anime but even better.
- The only regard I'd make is that the DLCs are quite expensive and the multiplayer lobby could be simplified. There are simply too many ways to join a fight and that might segregate the player base sometimes. 
- I haven't played the story mode yet but had a lot of fun in local and online multiplayer modes.

This game has
-Stunnning graphics;
-Lots of depth (for someone new to fighting games);
-easy commands and timings;
-story, arcade, tutorial and training mode;
-lots of characters.
Besides these points, I feel like DBFZ is true to the 'feel' you get when watching or reading Dragonball Z/Super, i.e. it's eccentric, overpowered and absurd. P.S. Spirit Bomb is in the game (Base Goku DLC though)
